<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>BUR 28</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Global Partners Governance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the author</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Greg Power</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been involved in political and parliamentary reform for around 20 years. He co-founded Global Partners in 2005 to deliver projects to strengthen representative politics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, since working in countries in the Middle East, sub-Saharan Africa and Latin America</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">He </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides direct support to politicians and ministers, developing strategies and helping to manage the process of political </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and parliamentary reform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">He has also provided advice to a variety of international organisations and donor agencies helping, amongst others, the Danish foreign ministry to establish their multi-party institute, and International IDEA to evaluate their work on political parties.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> He writes widely on issues such as the application of political economy analysis, donor approaches to governance assistance, and parliamentary transparency. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">He is the author of the first </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Global Parliamentary Report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published by the UNDP and IPU in 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Parliaments are central to the process of democratic transition.  They play an important role in determining the quality of governance by ensuring greater transparency and accountability. But they are also important for the international donor community in that parliaments provide a way to engage with every policy area connected with political and economic development.  Equally significant though is their role in shaping the public’s attitudes and expectations of the new democracy.  The institution’s performance in those early years plays a critical role in establishing the norms and values which shape the democratic culture.  Their performance will go a long way to determining how bumpy the transition to democracy is.  And, as the primary space for national social dialogue and negotiation between different interests, the parliament will be critical in securing and entrenching an inclusive political settlement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission considers the importance of parliamentary assistance within DFID’s programme of support for the development of democratic institutions in Burma.  Specifically, it examines:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.3pt; padding-left:7.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of the Burmese Parliament in the process of transition.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.83pt; padding-left:5.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The challenges of parliamentary strengthening during a transitional period.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.35pt; padding-left:2.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Key principles for parliamentary strengthening in Burma</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Parliamentary assistance strategies need to be built around a sophisticated understanding of how the institution works, and the incentive structures at play.  The submission suggests the use of political economy analysis could be used more effectively in this area, and would sharpen support to parliaments more generally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Burmese parliament in the process of transition.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The 2012 elections in Burma were seen as indication of the Burmese government’s intention to reform.  Although only 45 seats of the 440 member parliament were contested, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aung</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> San </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Suu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kyi’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> National League for Democracy (NLD) won 43 of them.  The regime’s Union Solidarity and Development Party (USDP), still retains 259 seats, and with 110 seats reserved for the military, the government still appears to have a lock on the legislature. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, since those elections the parliament has shown an increasing assertiveness and willingness to challenge the government.  Much is attributed to the leadership of the speaker, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thura</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Shwe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Mann.  A former Chief of the Armed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forces ,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> he was elected as Speaker in 2011, but far from simply doing the government’s bidding, he appears to be using the parliament as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">counterweight to executive control.  Shortly after taking office he began to address the problem of corruption in the public sector, and strengthening the parliament to improve its oversight of government.  Many commentators have suggested that his desire to strengthen the legislature is in part to position himself as a presidential candidate in the 2015 elections.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, the changed composition of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pyithu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Hluttaw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> appears to have created institutional momentum with the NLD MPs, and those from ethnic minorities, changing the way in which parliament works.  The NLD is proposing legislation, the committees are initiating investigations and challenging government policy, and USDP members seem more willing to utilise parliamentary powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the last couple of years the parliament has taken on a symbolic value in the process of reform, but also increasingly acted as a tangible means for challenging and changing the balance of power.  It offers the potential for greater oversight, tackling corruption, managing ethnic tension, and improving the quality of law.  But it has a large and growing legislative agenda, increasing public expectations of its performance and a wider desire to reform the political system.  And it faces numerous problems, common to many parliaments going through the transition to democracy, with limited democratic experience amongst both MPs and staff, a lack of internal organisation, and structures not suited to meet its expectations.  In short, it is in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a hurry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but lacking the experience and capacity to get things done quickly. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">International assistance to strengthen parliaments</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The challenge for DFID, and all the international donor agencies is how best to support such a pivotal institution facing these challenges.  It is clear that most of the main donor agencies are trying to support parliamentary development, but that much of this work has stuttered over the last two years, with the parliament facing problems of overload, co-ordination and a capacity to absorb the support they are being offered.  (One recent meeting between an international implementer and an MP started with the words, “Nice to meet you, you are the 52</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> scoping mission I have met in the last two years.”)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are already some interesting and innovative approaches being deployed by various organisations, including some funded by DFID, to support work with committees and improve the process of legislative drafting.  But the wider danger is that the international donor agencies - with a genuine desire to help, but also needing to show ‘quick wins’ - fall back on traditional methods of parliamentary support, such as training, technical support and capacity building/resources.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While well-meaning, these traditional techniques have been almost entirely ineffective in tackling the wider problems of parliamentary development.  This approach to parliamentary strengthening rested on the assumption that provided a parliament had enough resources, properly trained staff and functional rules of procedure it would work well.  Yet the effectiveness of a parliament depends on more than structure and capacity.  Ultimately, it depends on politicians and staff using fully the tools and powers at their disposal to hold government to account.  By failing to engage with the underlying factors and specific circumstances that influence parliamentary (and political) behaviour, the potential impact of such programmes is immediately restricted.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, the traditional approach has tended to look for technical solutions to what are, ultimately, problems of politics and political behaviour.  The most basic intention of parliamentary support should be to help MPs and staff do their jobs better.  But this means that such work should not just seek to change the structure of the institution, but to change the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behaviour of the politicians within it.  This, in turn, means first understanding the institutional and political incentive structures that are shaping that parliamentary behaviour.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="629" height="188" alt="" style="margin-left:0.65pt; margin-top:2.55pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID deserves much credit for pushing the use of political economy analysis in understanding such drivers of change.  But few international donor agencies are making rigorous use of such analytical techniques in their efforts to support parliaments and political parties.  Ironically, it seems that political economy analysis is used most sparingly in the areas that are most immediately political.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the Burmese context it means understanding not only the technical and resource constraints that inhibit parliament’s work, but also the political and cultural factors.  In Burma (as in most of the parliaments in the Arab world going through the transition from authoritarian rule to more representative politics) the lack of democratic experience means that the parliament has few precedents and commonly-understood procedures.  In short, it lacks a common political culture that informs and shapes the behaviour of both politicians and staff in the parliament.  In these early years, Members of Parliament are not only attempting to establish new rules of the game, but also to establish the informal rules that shape how the game is played.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The politics of parliamentary strengthening</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A more sophisticated approach to parliamentary strengthening would involve greater analysis of incentive structures within the Burmese parliament, the influence of key figures such as the Speaker and the roles of the different political parties.  This would inform a much more comprehensive political strategy, with multiple points of entry into the parliament.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a paper of this length it is impossible to provide a detailed political economy analysis of the Burmese parliaments and parties.  But, in one of our previous publications we identified three mains forms of incentives which shape parliamentary behaviour revolving around personal, political and institutional incentive structures.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  With that framework in mind, there are three general points worth emphasising: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Committees as models of good practice.</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We start by noting that politicians do not learn how to be politicians by being trained.  Learning how to be a member of parliament is a process of socialisation, with new MPs being influenced by interaction with their longer-standing colleagues and the advice of their parties.  Too much international donor assistance is aimed at poorly-constructed induction programmes which are too theoretical, fail to tackle the issues about which MPs are most concerned, and are quickly forgotten by the recipients.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A better strategy is to develop models of good practice in political behaviour, both amongst individual MPs and especially through committees.  Evidence from parliaments around the world show that an effective political technique will be absorbed and copied by many other MPs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For international parliamentary assistance, one of the best routes for this is through the parliamentary committees.  The committees provide a forum where politicians will work over a prolonged period with members of other parties, and allowing each of them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to  build</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> up a detailed policy expertise.  Committees provide the means and the opportunity for parliament to challenge government policy, finance and legislation.  Ensuring that one or two committees work effectively is likely to have a wider impact on the committee system, as others copy their approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ii.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Building i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nstitutional memory</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The lack of a common political culture in developing parliaments is often exacerbated by a high turnover of MPs at each election.  The first few elections of a new parliament will frequently see a turnover rate of anywhere between 60% and 80%.  In this environment, attempting to embed procedural precedents, standard ways of working, or even common acceptance of what the rules mean, is challenging.  The risk for international assistance is that much of the work to support MPs over three or four years can be lost in an electoral upheaval.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the Burmese context it seems likely that many of the current MPs are unlikely to still be there after 2015.  Support to the parliament therefore has to find ways of retaining institutional memory that does not depend solely on the presence of the same MPs.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Within the institution, there are three key groups which will do much to shape behaviour, but which are often overlooked for this purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First, support to the key institutional figures such as the Speaker, Secretary General, Committee chairs and should be seen as a way of creating a broader institutional culture.  Not only will such figures being important in establishing the tone of discussion and debate, but they also offer a way of creating new processes and precedents within the rules.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Second, although international support to political parties is increasing, most of that work goes on outside parliament.  Such support has largely missed the opportunities of working with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parties inside parliament</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> parliamentary party is likely to be a significant (and possibly the single most important) influence on how an MP behaves.  Parliamentary business is built around negotiations between the different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blocs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and an effective parliament depends on parliamentary parties that have a degree of coherence and cohesion.  Working with the parliamentary parties on organisation, structure and approach is essential during the development of any parliament.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Third, donor assistance needs to strengthen the role of the parliamentary staff as an authoritative and independent source of advice as to how the institution works.  One of the biggest contrasts between long-standing legislatures in Europe and North America, and more recently developed institutions elsewhere is in the role and status of parliamentary staff.  Parliaments need to ensure that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staff are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the repository for institutional knowledge, and a trusted source of advice for MPs.  Staff structures should be designed around retaining institutional memory.  This point is elaborated below.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">iii.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The importance of staff and internal structures</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staff of the parliament are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> often regarded as of secondary importance in international parliamentary assistance programmes.  However, training staff is likely to be most valuable in the development of institutional memory and the long-term effectiveness of the institution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is vital that staff should be able to advise MPs on procedure and process, but they should also enhance the ability of MPs to undertake their critical legislative, oversight and representative functions.  Many new parliaments are though hampered by a lack of quality staff, and also by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an unwillingness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by MPs in such contexts to delegate matters to staff.  The effect is to undermine the effectiveness of the MP and parliament, and to prevent the continuing development of a professional staff cadre.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Assistance in this area needs to strengthen the skills and authority of the staff.  At the most basic level it means a proper staff structure with job descriptions, training and clear lines of internal accountability and responsibility.  But it also means that new parliaments need to ensure that their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staff have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a career path within parliament, so that they are incentivised to stay and develop within the institution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By the same token, MPs in many new parliaments confuse the delegation of tasks with abdicating decision-making to staff.  Programmes need to ensure that MPs become effective delegators, understanding that staff support enhance the quality of decisions rather than undermining it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Parliament and political transition</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Burma the parliament will be pivotal in addressing a number of the challenges during the transition to democracy.  There is broad-based public support for the parliament, but the public perception of parliament is likely to be shaped by how the institution responds to those challenges of transition in the next few years.  They exist at three levels.  First the parliament it will be a key player in shaping the constitutional rules by which Burma develops.  Second, it will be judged by its ability to restrain the power of the Executive and deal with corruption.  Third, it is likely to be judged by citizens as to what it delivers for them in terms of standards of living and tangible changes to their lives.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The task for DFID, and other international donor agencies, is to recognise the especially important role performed by parliament in emerging democracies.  An effective parliament provides the connective tissue between people and power.  It is the main means for improving, oversight, accountability and the quality of governance, by ensuring that government priorities reflect and respond to the needs of the people.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supporting this process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will depend on a strategy which understands, and works with, the political dynamics that shape parliamentary behaviour and performance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Power, G. (2011), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">The Politics of Parliamentary Strengthening</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> - </span><a href="C:\Users\Greg.PC20-PC\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Content.Outlook\7LXYHRS3\www.gpgovernance.net\publication\the-politics-of-parliamentary-strengthening\"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gpgovernance.net/publication/the-politics-of-parliamentary-strengthening/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">See Power, G. and Shoot, R. (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">eds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">), (2012), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Political Parties in Transition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, DIPD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> which was launched in Yangon in February this year and is now available in Burmese.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">  </span><a href="C:\Users\Greg.PC20-PC\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Content.Outlook\7LXYHRS3\www.gpgovernance.net\publication\political-parties-in-democratic-transitions\"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gpgovernance.net/publication/political-parties-in-democratic-transitions/</span></a></p></body></html>